canonical:
  title: 淮安公答河西元帥書
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 某啓今月某日忽奉手敎具審鈞候動止佳勝萬福其爲欣抃手與心會兼承過示謙挹先辱榮問至以華袞之褒賁飾陋質非予微分所敢當也今者聳聞節下承奉聖旨收撫遼東等路歡慶倍常但以江山阻隔靡由攀晤第增瞻戀而已炎序方仲惟兾爲天下自嗇以副予傾禱之心幸甚無任惶悚之至再拜謹啓
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 淮安公答河西元帥書
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 某啓今月某日。忽奉手敎。具審鈞候動止佳勝萬福。其爲欣抃。手與心會。兼承過示謙挹。先辱榮問。至以華袞之褒。賁飾陋質。非予微分所敢當也。今者聳聞節下承奉聖旨。收撫遼東等路。歡慶倍常。但以江山阻隔。靡由攀晤。第增瞻戀而已。炎序方仲。惟兾爲天下自嗇。以副予傾禱之心幸甚。無任惶悚之至。再拜謹啓。
korean:
  title: 회안공 답 하서원수 서
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: 아무개는 아룁니다. 이달 모일에 돌연 주신 편지를 받고 존체 안녕하시고 만복(萬福)하심을 다 알았습니다. 충심으로 기뻐서 손뼉을 치며 기뻐해 마지않습니다. 겸해서 지나치게 겸손함을 나타내시고 먼저 영광스럽게도 안부(安否)를 물어주시며 나아가서는 재상(宰相)의 신분으로서 이 천한 태생을 아름답게 꾸며 주신 것은 저의 미천한 분수로는 감히 당해 낼 바가 아닌 것입니다.이제 귀를 기울여 들으니 절하(節下)께서 성지(聖旨)를 받들어 요동 등의 지방을 안찰(按察)하게 되셨다 하니 반갑고 경사스러움이 평상시의 배나 됩니다. 그러나 강산이 가로막혀 만나뵐 방법이 없어 다만 그리움만 더할 뿐입니다.더위가 바야흐로 본격화 하였으니, 오직 바라건대 천하를 위하여 스스로 보중(保重)하시어 저의 간절히 기도하는 마음에 부합되게 하여 주시면 천만 다행이겠습니다.황송한 마음 그지없어 다 감당하지 못하겠습니다. 재배(再拜)하여 삼가 아룁니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0640_010_0120&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Response to the Commander of the Western Region, the Lord of Huai'an
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant presents this letter on the [specific date] of this month. I have just received your gracious correspondence, and from it I have learned that your esteemed self enjoys perfect health and ten thousand blessings. My heart leaps with joy, and I cannot help but clap my hands in delight. Moreover, you have shown such modesty and restraint, first honoring me with your inquiry after my welfare, and then bestowing upon me praise beyond my station—adorning this humble and insignificant person with words befitting a minister of state. Such grace far exceeds what my meager station deserves.

    Now, hearing that you have received the Sacred Mandate to govern and bring order to Liaodong and the surrounding regions, my joy and celebration know no bounds—doubled and redoubled beyond measure. Yet alas, mountains and rivers stand between us, making it impossible for me to pay my respects in person. Thus my longing and affection can only grow with each passing day.

    As the summer heat reaches its height, I humbly entreat you to preserve your health and well-being for the sake of all under heaven, that you may fulfill the earnest prayers that flow unceasingly from my heart. This would be my greatest fortune. My reverence and anxiety are beyond measure. I bow twice and respectfully submit this letter.
  footnotes:
    - Lee Gyeong-bo (1168-1241) was a prominent Goryeo scholar-official and poet. This letter is addressed to a regional commander who has been appointed to administrative duties.
    - The formal structure of this letter follows classical Chinese epistolary conventions, with ritualistic expressions of gratitude, modesty, and well-wishing toward the recipient's new appointment.
    - References to 'ten thousand blessings' (萬福) and the 'Sacred Mandate' (聖旨) reflect the hierarchical and Sinocentric worldview of medieval Korea.
